"Over the past year the IT press has been full of news stories announcing that a supplier or service provider has recently formed “a strategic partnership”, “a working partnership”, “an alliance” or has entered a “partnering” agreement with another company, in order to complete a particular project (or a series of similar protects) or to outsource its IT requirement. This article attempts to unravel the legal reality behind the hype. Are these agreements simply a form of Joint venture under another, more appealing label; or do they represent genuine partnerships and/or are partnering arrangements? I start by looking at the characteristics of a partnering agreement. Thereafter I explain broadly the relevance of partnering to IT projects generally and how the concept is beginning to be used in practice under various forms of contract.The third section of this article considers the contractual implications of partnering arrangements upon the IT projects identified in the preceding section. I then seek to distinguish partnering from a joint venture or partnership. Finally I draw a tentative conclusion."
